Devil&#x27;s advocate example:<p><pre><code>  union hack { int x; float y};

  int foo( int *i, float *f)
  {
     *i = 3;
     *f = 42.0;
     return *i;
  }
</code></pre>
Aliasing rules say foo need not read from that int pointer, may switch the order of the write to f and the write to i, and can assume that foo returns 3, so<p><pre><code>  struct hack h;

  foo( &h.i, &h.f);
</code></pre>
might return 3 or something else. I think that last call introduces undefined behavior, but only becuase of the definition of foo that the writer of that call might not even have the source for.<p>But of course, that is an &quot;you shouldn&#x27;t do that&quot; edge case. One could also claim that the corrigendum doesn&#x27;t apply because foo doesn&#x27;t &quot;use a member to access the contents of a union&quot;.
